The paper deals with dynamic algorithms for interval scheduling, which is a classic problem in computer science. The focus is on the case when the set of intervals is monotonic, which is a specific property of the input that can be exploited to design efficient algorithms. The paper presents two data structures for representing the intervals and analyzes their performance in terms of insertion, removal, and query operations. These are typical topics in the field of data structures and algorithms, which are covered by several arXiv CS sub-categories. Based on the abstract, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which is the main area of research for the paper. Other relevant sub-categories are cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), cs.AL (Computational Complexity), cs.CC (Computational Complexity and Cryptography), and cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
